settlement-12-world-primer.html.title: Settlement 12 World Primer
settlement-12-world-primer.html.description: Several hundred years ago, an event known as the Great Eruption caused the functional collapse of the society of the old world. The new world is built on the technological and cultural remnants of the old world, but it also incorporates the newly-emerged neoscience, also known as magic.The continent that contains Settlement 12 has various regions. From west to east, they are:A long coast, boreal in the north and subtropical in the south. Has several major cities, including San Júpiter and Lacey City.A mountain range not far from the west coast.A large desert between the Norilla Minors and the Norilla Majors. Because of how dry it is, there are few landmarks in this region-most trains travel right though it without stopping.A mountain range east of the Expanse, this mountain range is significantly taller and larger than the Norilla Minors. It is littered with traditional Jovian communities.A vast grassland east of the Norilla Majors. Settlement 12 is on its west edge, while the central grasslands have many farming communities.The farther east one travels, the more toxic the air, water and soil become. On the eastern Solar Plains, farming is difficult. East of that is a hardy forested region known as the Deadlands because of its environmental hostility. The continent-wide railroad lines end in the west Deadlands, where some people scrape out a meager living in the short term (staying here for longer than a year or two can have serious health impacts). The eastern Deadlands are completely uninhabitable, and only receive occasional visits from archeologists looking to study its copious old world ruins.

info_showOrphanNodes.description: Show nodes that are not connected to any other nodes.

info_showAttachments.description: Show attachments like images and PDFs as nodes in the graph.

info_allowGlobalGraph.description: Allow the user to view the global graph of all nodes.

info_allowExpand.description: Allow the user to pop-out the graph view to take up the whole screen

info_attractionForce.description: How much should linked nodes attract each other? This will make the graph appear more clustered.

info_linkLength.description: How long should the links between nodes be? The shorter the links the more connected nodes will cluster together.

info_repulsionForce.description: How much should nodes repel each other? This will make disconnected parts more spread out.

info_centralForce.description: How much should nodes be attracted to the center? This will make the graph appear more dense and circular.

info_edgePruning.description: Edges with a length above this threshold will not be rendered, however they will still contribute to the simulation. This can help large tangled graphs look more organised. Hovering over a node will still display these links.

info_minNodeRadius.description: How small should the smallest nodes be? The smaller a node is the less it will attract other nodes.

info_maxNodeRadius.description: How large should the largest nodes be? Nodes are sized by how many links they have. The larger a node is the more it will attract other nodes. This can be used to create a good grouping around the most important nodes.
